                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                     CBI nails Kidney Kumar
          OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT                              
	New Delhi, April 29: The Central Bureau of Investigation has filed a chargesheet against Amit Kumar, the main accused in the multi-crore kidney transplant racket, and eight others.        
	The CBI, finding overwhelming evidence against Kumar, has charged him with attempt to murder, cheating, conspiracy and also crimes under the Transplant of Human Organs Act.        
	Amit Kumar, whose real name is Santosh Kumar Raut, was arrested from Chitwan on the Nepal border on February 7.        
	Armed with a degree in ayurvedic medicine, he allegedly carried out over 500 illegal kidney transplants  something he was not trained to do.        
	He was assisted by his brother Jeevan, a homoeopath. They have been accused of forcing or duping 500 people, most of them poor, into parting with their kidneys.        
	The CBI investigations revealed that since 1995, eight criminal cases had been registered against Kumar in Mumbai, Jaipur, Guntur and Delhi. All of them related to illegal kidney transplants.         
	For the last few years, Kumar had been conducting the kidney transplants in a clandestine hospital established and owned by him at Palam Vihar in Gurgaon, on the outskirts of Delhi.        
	The other accused include Upendra Aggarwal, Saraj Kovid and a nurse employed with the Ram Manohar Lohia Hospital.                                                                                                                                                                         
